Went by their drive through on a Saturday afternoon. Pretty decent line of cars, perhaps waited around 5-10 minutes to put our order in and get our custard, so not too bad. Employees had face coverings on (much appreciated!).  I tried their soggy bottom, which is basically vanilla custard, with peanut butter sauce and crushed oreos at the bottom. Portions are big. Prices are very reasonable. There was plenty of peanut butter on there (maybe a little too much?) and not enough oreos :( but the flavors were good. They use the environmentally hazardous styrofoam type dishes which was really disappointing to see. Overall, a pretty average experience.  In response to what the owner has posted: Thank you for taking the time to reply to my review. I really appreciate that.  It's good IF the styrofoam is being recycled. But this is only if the customer makes the effort to dispose of the containers in a recycling bin. Styrofoam is a petroleum based product. Thus, its production and destruction (in landfills) is toxic to the environment. When exposed to certain levels of sun, it can burn releasing toxic chemicals into the air. Even hot liquids and foods can cause the partial breakdown of styrofoam, causing us to ingest harmful toxins. There are some wonderful new materials out on the market that do not exact a toll on the environment or humans in its production or in its disposal (whether they are recycled or not!).

My friend has raved about this place for years.  As a devout ice-cream-lover, I have my own favorite (Sherman's in South Haven, MI) and dismissed his ravings as those of an ill-informed lunatic Hoosier.  With this in mind, I nevertheless decided that I should visit and see for myself.  I am forced to admit that, as custard goes, it is top-notch.  Most custard is fairly dense- this is lighter, smoother, more delicate, with rich flavor.  It's a definite step-up from most custards I've tried.  And while it will never replace ice-cream IMHO, for custard, it is definitely the cream (and eggs) of the crop.
